hat these strategies matter greatly to international stability and it provides new insights into conflict dynamics across important areas of the world such as the Middle East, East Asia, and South Asia.Vipin Narang identifies the diversity of regional power nuclear strategies and describes in detail the posture each regional power has adopted over time. Developing a theory for the sources of regional power nuclear strategies, he offers the first systematic explanation of why states choose the postures they do and under what conditions they might shift strategies. Narang then analyzes the effects of these choices on a state's ability to deter conflict. Using both quantitative and qualitative analysis, he shows that, contrary to a bedrock article of faith in the canon of nuclear deterrence, the acquisition of nuclear weapons does not produce a uniform deterrent effect against opponents. Rather, some postures deter conflict more successfully than others.Nuclear Strategy in the Modern Era considers the range of nuclear choices made by regional powers and the critical challenges they pose to modern international security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeterrence (Strategy)vCase studies. 0aNuclear warfarexGovernment policyvCase studies. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAvner Cohen.  aChina.  aCold War.  aFrance.  aIndia.  aIsrael.  aIsraeli officials.  aPakistan.  aPosture Optimization Theory.  aSouth Africa.  aSoviet Union.  aWestern assistance.  aalliance options.  aassured retaliation.  aasymmetric escalation.  aasymmetric nuclear posture.  acatalytic nuclear posture.  acivilian control.  acivilЭilitary relations.  acloset nuclear state.  acon